diff:1619304647:1619304647:=1,76d0%0a%3c :Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a%3c :Expansion: An equivalent in Japanese%0a%3c :Author: JacobF%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.CanadianEh|CanadianEh]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.nithyas|nithyas]]%0a%3c :Section: A%0a%3c :Completed: 24.04.2021 - 15:50%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c In Japanese, various 'particles' are inserted between words to identify their relationship with one another (on problem set 4, 'ga' 'o' and 'wa' are all examples of particles).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c The particle 'ne' (ね) may be appended to a sentence to change its tone to one of asking for confirmation. Interestingly, this almost identically maps to the Canadian Eh, in that they both appear sentence-finally, and both change an assertion into that of a questioning (and they sound a little similar). This works both for positive and negative sentences.%0a%3c %0a%3c For example,%0a%3c %0a%3c 'anata no  tomodachi no namae  wa     Clark desu'%0a%3c   you  pos  friend   pos name  topic  Clark is%0a%3c your friend's name is clark%0a%3c %0a%3c vs%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 'anata no  tomodachi no namae  wa     Clark desu ne'%0a%3c   you  pos  friend   pos name  topic  Clark is   eh%0a%3c your friend's name is clark, right?%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (pos is short for possesion)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c and also%0a%3c %0a%3c 'kore   wa  niku ja nai desu' %0a%3c  that topic meat   not   is%0a%3c  that is not meat%0a%3c %0a%3c versus%0a%3c %0a%3c 'kore   wa  niku ja nai desu ne'%0a%3c  that topic meat   not   is  eh%0a%3c  that is not meat, is it?%0a%3c %0a%3c Source:%0a%3c %0a%3c Banno, Eri, et al. An Integrated Course in Elementary Japanese. The Japan Times, 2011. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
